INT. HARVEY AND RSDOIEL TALKING 2026-04-17 17:15:00

Harvey and RSDOIEL are in chat mode. Model: CLAUDE. Workspace: /Users/rsdoiel/Laboratory/harvey.

RSDOIEL
I want to evaluate an idea. If recording is on and we produce a Fountain
file, would it be possible to read the file and re-run the Fountain
document in Harvey?

HARVEY
Forwarding to CLAUDE.

CLAUDE
Yes, feasible. The fountain.ParseFile() function already exists in the
dependency. Two distinct interpretations: Option A (ContinueFromFountain)
— parse the file, reconstruct conversation history, start Harvey so the
user can continue from that point. Option B (ReplayFromFountain) — re-send
each USER dialogue line to the LLM as a live message, get fresh responses,
record a new Fountain. Option A is instant with no LLM cost; Option B
re-infers and is useful for model comparison or regression testing.


INT. HARVEY AND RSDOIEL TALKING 2026-04-17 17:20:00

Harvey and RSDOIEL are in chat mode. Model: CLAUDE. Workspace: /Users/rsdoiel/Laboratory/harvey.

RSDOIEL
Is it possible to support both options? ContinueFromFountain for Option A,
ReplayFromFountain for Option B. A2: write-file actions in replay should
backup the original then write the new version. If not writable, note as
skipped in the new Fountain. Use case: collaborate between Claude Code and
Harvey without MCP — Claude writes a Fountain, Harvey continues or replays.

HARVEY
Forwarding to CLAUDE.

CLAUDE
Yes, both are supported cleanly. They share a parseFountainSession core
that walks Elements and extracts PlaybackTurn structs. ContinueFromFountain
pre-populates Agent history; ReplayFromFountain iterates user inputs, calls
Chat(), applies code blocks with timestamped backup protection
(file.bak.YYYYMMDD-HHMMSS), and records to a new Fountain. The Fountain
file becomes a shared handoff protocol between Claude Code and Harvey —
human-readable and requiring no live connection between agents.


